If I may add another, more abstract motivation to Kai and Eleanor's=20
security concerns: signatures help move authority out of centralized=20
silos and towards users (especially for PGP, though even S/MIME is a=20
more distributed trust model than just server-side validation). Right=20
now, users have to have a considerable amount of confidence in their=20
email provider, both that the provider itself would not do anything=20
nefarious (e.g., inserting ads or trackers into emails you send), and=20
that they are sufficiently skilled at preventing/handling compromise. In=20
practice, this looks like decades of "just use Yahoo/GMail/Microsoft"=20
advice to average users for securing mail, since these are the providers=20
that are "too big to fail". Implicitly signing all emails is part of the=20
process of being able to shift that trust away from the provider and=20
towards user's devices. While I would of course love encrypted mail to=20
be the default, signing gets us closer to that user-side trust, and is a=20
lot less likely to cause breakage. It is in many ways true that the=20
utility of signatures is proportional to the ability to expect one, but=20
that was true for HTTPS certificates too, and now look where we=20
are=E2=80=94browsers that warn when a site doesn't have one. "Every journey=
=20
starts with a single step", and all that.

  - Justin


